<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1440,321,506]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,336,321,345]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2015" box="[342,630,322,346]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitator">
<emphasis box="[342,630,322,346]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Paraberismyia imitator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other species in the genus by having the abdomen uniformly brown, without yellowish areas medially on tergites (
<figureCitation box="[1135,1235,354,378]" captionStart="Figures 1–3" captionStartId="5.[192,288,1875,1897]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,685,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-104@5.[192,1440,685,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 1–3. Holotype male of Paraberismyia imitator, n. sp. 1) Dorsal habitus view. 2) Left lateral habitus view (mirror image). 3) Anterior view of head. Figure 4. Male of Berismyia fusca Giglio-Tos. 4) Anterior view of head." pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1, 2</figureCitation>
). In my previous key (
<bibRefCitation author="Woodley, N. E." box="[251,473,386,410]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="25 - 45" refId="ref2960" refString="Woodley, N. E. 2013. A revision of the Neotropical genus Paraberismyia Woodley (Diptera, Stratiomyidae, Beridinae) with three new species. ZooKeys 353: 25 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Woodley 2013: 27</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2015" box="[495,630,386,409]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitator">
<emphasis box="[495,630,386,409]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">P. imitator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will not key to any species because at couplet 2, while cell cu 
<emphasis box="[1395,1410,386,409]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">p</emphasis>
is completely covered with microtrichia, the first tarsomere of the hind leg is completely pale so one cannot proceed to couplet 3. Thus, the key could be modified so that at couplet 1, when choosing “males” it leads to couplet 1a:
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
