<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,706,793]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,348,706,730]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2015" box="[602,703,706,729]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitator">
<emphasis box="[602,703,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">imitator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a noun in apposition referring to the fact that this species has the general appearance of a species of 
<taxonomicName box="[705,830,738,761]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Berismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[705,830,738,761]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Berismyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather than the other known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="1995" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1441,834,1178]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,323,834,858]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2015" box="[328,612,834,858]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitator">
<emphasis box="[328,612,834,858]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia imitator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is yet another species of the genus found in the highlands of Chiapas. Remarkably, all known specimens of the genus were collected at only three localities. All four species treated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Woodley, N. E." box="[319,502,898,922]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="25 - 45" refId="ref2960" refString="Woodley, N. E. 2013. A revision of the Neotropical genus Paraberismyia Woodley (Diptera, Stratiomyidae, Beridinae) with three new species. ZooKeys 353: 25 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Woodley (2013)</bibRefCitation>
were collected at El Triunfo, Chiapas, in May, 1985. This site is at the southern end of the Sierra Madre de Chiapas. One of these, 
<taxonomicName authority="Woodley" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="1995" box="[808,1105,930,954]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tzontehuitza">
<emphasis box="[808,991,930,954]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">P. tzontehuitza</emphasis>
Woodley
</taxonomicName>
, had been described earlier (
<bibRefCitation author="Woodley, N. E." box="[200,431,961,986]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 231" refId="ref2929" refString="Woodley, N. E. 1995. The genera of Beridinae (Diptera: Stratiomyidae). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Washington 16: 1 - 231." type="journal article" year="1995">Woodley 1995: 136</bibRefCitation>
) from Cerro Tzontehuitz, Chiapas, which is in the Central Highlands. The species described herein is from the same locality. Old specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2013" box="[949,1224,994,1018]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triunfo">
<emphasis box="[949,1224,994,1018]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia triunfo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected in 
<collectingRegion box="[192,348,1026,1050]" country="Guatemala" name="Totonicapan" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Totonicapán</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[360,500,1026,1050]" name="Guatemala" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, which is in the Sierra Madre that is essentially a southern extension of the Sierra Madre de Chiapas. Given the relatively little amount of collecting that has been done in this region and the number of species already known from this area, it seems very likely that still more species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="1995" box="[315,496,1122,1146]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[315,496,1122,1146]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will be discovered. It also indicates that the highland regions of Chiapas and adjacent 
<collectingCountry box="[304,441,1154,1178]" name="Guatemala" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
are biodiverse and rich in endemic species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
